   579‚Üí## Docs
   580‚Üí
   581‚ÜíDotenv exposes four functions:
   582‚Üí
   583‚Üí* `config`
   584‚Üí* `parse`
   585‚Üí* `populate`
   586‚Üí
   587‚Üí### Config
   588‚Üí
   589‚Üí`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590‚Üí[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591‚Üíand return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592‚Üí
   593‚Üí```js
   594‚Üíconst result = dotenv.config()
   595‚Üí
   596‚Üíif (result.error) {
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   605‚Üí#### Options
   606‚Üí
   607‚Üí##### path
   608‚Üí
   609‚ÜíDefault: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610‚Üí
   611‚ÜíSpecify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612‚Üí
   613‚Üí```js
   614‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615‚Üí```
   616‚Üí
   617‚ÜíBy default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618‚Üí
   619‚ÜíPass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620‚Üí
   621‚Üí```js  
   622‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623‚Üí```
   624‚Üí
   625‚Üí##### quiet
   626‚Üí
   627‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   628‚Üí
   629‚ÜíSuppress runtime logging message.
   630‚Üí
   631‚Üí```js
   632‚Üí// index.js
   633‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634‚Üíconsole.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   648‚Üí##### encoding
   649‚Üí
   650‚ÜíDefault: `utf8`
   651‚Üí
   652‚ÜíSpecify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653‚Üí
   654‚Üí```js
   655‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656‚Üí```
   657‚Üí
   658‚Üí##### debug
   659‚Üí
   660‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   661‚Üí
   662‚ÜíTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663‚Üí
   664‚Üí```js
   665‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666‚Üí```
   667‚Üí
   668‚Üí##### override
   669‚Üí
   670‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   671‚Üí
   672‚ÜíOverride any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673‚Üí
   674‚Üí```js
   675‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676‚Üí```
   677‚Üí
   678‚Üí##### processEnv
   679‚Üí
   680‚ÜíDefault: `process.env`
   681‚Üí
   682‚ÜíSpecify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683‚Üí
   684‚Üí```js
   685‚Üíconst myObject = {}
   686‚Üírequire('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   692‚Üí### Parse
   693‚Üí
   694‚ÜíThe engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695‚Üívariables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696‚Üían Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697‚Üí
   698‚Üí```js
   699‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700‚Üíconst buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701‚Üíconst config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   705‚Üí#### Options
   706‚Üí
   707‚Üí##### debug
   708‚Üí
   709‚ÜíDefault: `false`
   710‚Üí
   711‚ÜíTurn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712‚Üí
   713‚Üí```js
   714‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715‚Üíconst buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716‚Üíconst opt = { debug: true }
   717‚Üíconst config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718‚Üí// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719‚Üí```
   720‚Üí
   721‚Üí### Populate
   722‚Üí
   723‚ÜíThe engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724‚Üí
   725‚ÜíFor example, customizing the source:
   726‚Üí
   727‚Üí```js
   728‚Üíconst dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729‚Üíconst parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730‚Üí
